Zj1RGcOpCzkiaPu9lYaYwVzpLv5nL_C9hL5_v7-9PnlS5emg7qVTM2gVeKSOq0t0o4Z_qgwHEBMwBupYmhGXr10M5s3nCVGN6xjmXIRXL7bUSfE3wo1Fsl3Tvovc59a5O6dVaRmWUseSbQ0oQIx5GPoqyqBaIFAZOdaURfo18eopUQjoH7nseyl-UE9-yGplG4aMr-0_8ovbUcQb6WG_OFxCK2U2LLVSkkSlzKZJWzCQcAE_CoDHHj5Cp4TNJjdmYXAEjrBtq-d9FKoBupSQbU3UriVfGwvdCydRK4kaW3WpP5FQEiBysw9TmxTOeyDjV00mOyNV2QCb-2aXNeI6PqOTb_vYTV7nfrqQhYs-GD6hen0TXLC5FOo8ix2icEq3Hko9pOBhHeBzz7-Vt-rCRgPshDaa6HNeYHLHY6jYyhR41wXHSEywpJ66X3CIdjcxjvP4B3VDM27nob6CvUUq-K6v_aNXh6G2u8PtFtuo-q6PkCkOmipdBaD6KT7m-wD68a9P7Xn-RKU-SSfc4_K2rMNUU-HkdpD_VJEEsyYJWiXrBVF8w57VeUAvx4jrYdn86hxlRv-gdu6FmT0=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering agent execution**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether I should gather information directly with the agent. But what if I run a native test before using the agent? It’s a bit confusing, and I wonder which approach will yield better results. Should I prioritize data collection with the agent, or is the native test run essential to inform the agent's behavior? I guess I need to weigh the options carefully!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating serialization in native images**\\n\\nI’m examining the serialization issues related to `ProvDHPrivateKey` where a lack of metadata could halt the `writeObject` call. Since Native Image relies on serialization configuration, it could lead to `MissingSerializationRegistrationError` at runtime. Forge generates metadata externally, which might be problematic for tests if missing the right class. It seems we can't edit metadata, but I wonder how we can run tests if the metadata isn't there, especially with dynamic coverage reports in the picture.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating test runtime coverage**\\n\\nI'm looking into an issue where if a test throws at runtime, it results in no coverage. I wonder if I can catch `MissingSerializationRegistrationError`, but skipping over missing metadata doesn’t seem right. The goal of dynamic access is essential. It's possible that `ObjectOutputStream#writeObject(privateKey)` may not be tracked properly in user code due to filters. Maybe I need to check the class name mapping, though I can’t use reflection directly. It seems like I need to refine the serialization paths in the test class while ensuring everything remains one-to-one.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining key generation and serialization**\\n\\nI’m looking at the `KeyFactory.generatePrivate` methods, particularly with `DHPrivateKeySpec` and `PKCS8EncodedKeySpec`. It's possible that the `ProvDHPrivateKey` constructor from `DHPrivateKeySpec` is returning the right class, but maybe the parameters cause `writeObject` to fail. The PKCS8 path suggests that `BaseKeyFactory` creates a new `ProvDHPrivateKey`. Since it's the same class, I could potentially cover that. I should also consider adding `writeUnshared` and `readUnshared` to enhance serialization.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_0itq0SzQyayjRXi5Aa65w24Z|fc_012bb78dfe5872dd016a3f8a47cf2c81948c9ecf4ba7460a48", "name": "edit", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.bouncycastle/bc-fips/2.1.2/src/test/java/org_bouncycastle/bc_fips/ProvDHPrivateKeyTest.java", "edits": [{"oldText": "import java.io.IOException;\nimport java.io.ObjectInputStream;\nimport java.io.ObjectOutputStream;\nimport java.io.ObjectStreamClass;\nimport java.math.BigInteger;\nimport java.security.KeyFactory;", "newText": "import java.io.ObjectInputStream;\nimport java.io.ObjectOutputStream;\nimport java.math.BigInteger;\nimport java.security.KeyFactory;"}, {"oldText": "import javax.crypto.spec.DHPrivateKeySpec;\n\nimport org.bouncycastle.jcajce.provider.BouncyCastleFipsProvider;", "newText": "import java.security.spec.PKCS8EncodedKeySpec;\n\nimport javax.crypto.spec.DHPrivateKeySpec;\n\nimport org.bouncycastle.jcajce.provider.BouncyCastleFipsProvider;"}, {"oldText": "    @Test\n    void serializationRoundTripRestoresDhPrivateKey() throws Exception {\n        DHPrivateKeySpec keySpec = new DHPrivateKeySpec(\n                PRIVATE_EXPONENT, MODP_2048_PRIME, GENERATOR);\n        PrivateKey privateKey = KeyFactory.getInstance(\"DH\", bouncyCastleFipsProvider())\n                .generatePrivate(keySpec);\n\n        assertEquals(PROVIDER_PRIVATE_KEY_CLASS_NAME, privateKey.getClass().getName());\n\n        PrivateKey deserializedKey = assertInstanceOf(\n                PrivateKey.class, deserialize(serialize(privateKey), privateKey.getClass()));\n        DHPrivateKey dhPrivateKey = assertInstanceOf(DHPrivateKey.class, deserializedKey);\n\n        assertEquals(PROVIDER_PRIVATE_KEY_CLASS_NAME, deserializedKey.getClass().getName());\n        assertEquals(\"DH\", deserializedKey.getAlgorithm());\n        assertEquals(PRIVATE_EXPONENT, dhPrivateKey.getX());\n        assertEquals(MODP_2048_PRIME, dhPrivateKey.getParams().getP());\n        assertEquals(GENERATOR, dhPrivateKey.getParams().getG());\n        assertArrayEquals(privateKey.getEncoded(), deserializedKey.getEncoded());\n    }\n", "newText": "    @Test\n    void serializationRoundTripRestoresDhPrivateKeyFromKeySpec() throws Exception {\n        DHPrivateKeySpec keySpec = new DHPrivateKeySpec(\n                PRIVATE_EXPONENT, MODP_2048_PRIME, GENERATOR);\n        PrivateKey privateKey = dhKeyFactory().generatePrivate(keySpec);\n\n        assertSerializationRoundTrip(privateKey);\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    void serializationRoundTripRestoresDhPrivateKeyFromPkcs8Encoding() throws Exception {\n        DHPrivateKeySpec keySpec = new DHPrivateKeySpec(\n                PRIVATE_EXPONENT, MODP_2048_PRIME, GENERATOR);\n        PrivateKey privateKey = dhKeyFactory().generatePrivate(keySpec);\n        PrivateKey pkcs8PrivateKey = dhKeyFactory().generatePrivate(\n                new PKCS8EncodedKeySpec(privateKey.getEncoded()));\n\n        assertSerializationRoundTrip(pkcs8PrivateKey);\n    }\n\n    private static void assertSerializationRoundTrip(PrivateKey privateKey) throws Exception {\n        ass